03958nam a22004815i 9780226414201DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20081998ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264142017 a10.7208/97802264142012doi  a(DE-B1597)524218  a(OCoLC)835922009  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aDC33.7.J83 2006 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a944.08/092/22211 aJudt, Tony, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Burden of Responsibility :bBlum, Camus, Aron, and the French Twentieth Century /cTony Judt. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (204 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tINTRODUCTION. The Misjudgment of Paris -- tOne. The Prophet Spurned. LÉON BLUM AND THE PRICE OF COMPROMISE -- tTWO. The Reluctant Moralist -- tTHREE. The Peripheral Insider -- tFurther Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUsing the lives of the three outstanding French intellectuals of the twentieth century, renowned historian Tony Judt offers a unique look at how intellectuals can ignore political pressures and demonstrate a heroic commitment to personal integrity and moral responsibility unfettered by the difficult political exigencies of their time. Through the prism of the lives of Leon Blum, Albert Camus, and Raymond Aron, Judt examines pivotal issues in the history of contemporary French society-antisemitism and the dilemma of Jewish identity, political and moral idealism in public life, the Marxist moment in French thought, the traumas of decolonization, the disaffection of the intelligentsia, and the insidious quarrels rending Right and Left. Judt focuses particularly on Blum's leadership of the Popular Front and his stern defiance of the Vichy governments, on Camus's part in the Resistance and Algerian War, and on Aron's cultural commentary and opposition to the facile acceptance by many French intellectuals of communism's utopian promise. Severely maligned by powerful critics and rivals, each of these exemplary figures stood fast in their principles and eventually won some measure of personal and public redemption. Judt constructs a compelling portrait of modern French intellectual life and politics. He challenges the conventional account of the role of intellectuals precisely because they mattered in France, because they could shape public opinion and influence policy. In Blum, Camus, and Aron, Judt finds three very different men who did not simply play the role, but evinced a courage and a responsibility in public life that far outshone their contemporaries. "An eloquent and instructive study of intellectual courage in the face of what the author persuasively describes as intellectual irresponsibility."-Richard Bernstein, New York Times  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226414201423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226414201.jpg  a978-3-11-066785-1  UChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles